@node "What" "What Is Archie?"
@next "why"
@prev "Main"
@{b}What Is Archie?@{ub}

Archie is an internet search tool that locates files stored at FTP
sites around the world. You give it it's instructions and it looks for the
files you want.
@endnode

@node "Why" "Why ArFiR?"
@next "How"
@prev "what"
@{b}Why ArFiR?@{ub}

I wrote ArFiR mainly because I saw pictures in magazines of
archie clients for the Mac and saw how easy to use they were. The standard
amiga client required you to enter several command line options and was
not therefore very user friendly. ArFiR provides an easy to use interface
which allows you to hunt for files and download them easily.
@endnode

@node "How" "How To Use ArFiR"
@next "Server"
@prev "Why"
@{b}How To Use ArFiR?@{ub}

Firstly type ArFiR.exe at a shell prompt or select the archie option
from AmiTCP Control Panel, or double click on the icon.

The following options are then available.

@{"Archie Server" link "server" 0}

@{"Search Text" link "search" 0}

@{"Case Sensitive" link "case" 0}

@{"Sub String" link "string" 0}

@{"Matches" link "matches" 0}

When you have entered all the details press @{"Start Search" link "start" 0} to start the
search or press @{"Cancel" link "how" 0} to cancel.
@endnode

@node "Server" "Archie Server"
@toc "How"
@prev "How"
@{b}Archie Server@{ub}

This is the archie server archie will search to find your required
search text, the default of archie.doc.ic.ac.uk should be appropriate for
most searches.  You can however change the address by clicking on the archie
host cycle gadget, all archie servers

You can set the environment variable ArchieDefault, inorder to select
which archie server is the first in the cycle gadget.

e.g.

setenv archiedefault archie.doc.ic.ac.uk

This will make archie.doc.ic.ac.uk the first server in the list.
@endnode

@node "search" "Search Text"
@toc "how"
@next "case"
@prev "server"
@{b}Search Text@{ub}

This is the most important part, choosing what to search for. Click in
the text entry box next to the words "Search Text", enter the text to search
for. This text will be acted upon by the Case Sensitive and Sub String
gadgets.
@endnode

@node "case" "Case Sensitive"
@toc "how"
@next "string"
@prev "server"
@{b}Case Sensitive@{ub}

If "Case Sensitive" is selected, indicated with a tick,Archie will check
the search text, and only show matches where the text is in the same case as
that entered. i.e. if you enter "Water", it will find "Water" but not "water".
To select/deselect just cl
@endnode

@node "string" "Sub String"
@toc "how"
@next "matches"
@prev "case"
@{b}Search Type@{ub}

There are 3 search types available from Arfir these are

Sub-String (default)

Exact

String Regular

Sub string will search for items which contain the search text anywhere in
the file or path name.

Exact string will search for the exact string to be found, this is good if
you know the full name of the file, but just need to find out where it is.

Regular allows you to enter regular expressions.

These search types can be selected by clicking on the radio buttons.
@endnode

@node "Matches" "Matches"
@toc "how"
@next "start"
@prev "string"
@{b}Matches@{ub}

The "Matches" option determines the maximum number of files Archie will
find. This number can be selected by moving the slider gadget or by entering
the number into the box next to the slider.
If you are using an unregistered version you will be limited to a maximum of
30 hits, this maximum is increased upto 250 (or higher by request) in the
registered version.
@endnode

@node "start" "Start Search"
@toc "how"
@next "problems"
@prev "matches"
@{b}Start Search@{ub}

Now that you have set the options you must now tell archie to get to work,
you do this by clicking on the button "Search Text", if you wish to cancel
the search just press @{"Cancel" link "start" 0}.

When archie has finished its search, if successful the results will
be outputted to a new window in which you may select the file/s and
download it/them.

@{"Download Files" link "Download Files" 0}
@endnode

@node "Download Files" "Download Files"
Download Files

The top portion of the display shows the files which archie has found, due
to limitations of space on a std screen this display doesn't show the
full details but enough for you to select the file. The size column shows how
big the file is in kilobytes, th

To get further information about an entry, click on the cycle gadget at
the bottom of the screen so that @{"information" link "" 0} is visible, then click on an item
in the list, the status display will then display the full name and batch of
the file, si

To download a file makesure that @{"download" link "" 0} is visible on the cycle gadget,
and that a valid pathname is selected in the download directory gadget,
this download directory can be selected from a filerequester by pressing the
D button or it ca

The final thing that the cycle gadget can show is @{"View File" link "" 0}, this allows
you to view the file you select, the program sees if multiview is available
and uses that to display the file. If multiview isn't available only text
files can be disp

The status display in the centre of the screen, shows additional
information about the selected options and also provides error messages and
other details.
@endnode

@node "Problems" "Problems"
@next "disclaimer"
@{b}Problems@{ub}

ArFiR Won't Work :-( If the answer to the following questions is no,
then Archie will not work and you need to make sure that all the answers are
yes, and then try again.

Is Amitcp started?
Are you connected?
Have you got FTPGet?
Are the username and hostname environment variables set?
Have you got an archie client?
Is this client named Archie? (if not rename it)
Is archie on a path? (can you run it from a cli without specifying a path)

Other Problems

Try using Archie by the old CLI method, does this work? If not it's
Archie's fault not mine. If Archie works by using CLI and not by GUI send me a
note explaining what the problem is, and I will do my best to help.
@endnode

@node "disclaimer" "Disclaimer"
@next "author"
